{
  "texts": [
    "The Q-values for each state-action pair are incrementally updated according to the TD error.",
    "This error, i.e., r+ max a � i Q i (s �, a � i) -Q i (s, a i), represents the difference between a new estimate (i.e., r + max a � i Q i (s �, a � i)) and the current estimate (i.e., Q i (s, a i)) based on the Bellman equation [25].",
    "As the state and action space could be too large to be encountered frequently for accurate estimation, function approximation methods, like deep neural networks, have become popular for endowing value or policy models with generalization abilities across both discrete and continuous states and actions [12].",
    "For example, the Deep Q-network (DQN) [12] minimizes the difference between the new estimate calculated from sampled rewards and the current estimate of a parameterized Q-function.",
    "In DQN-based methods, the Q-function in Eq. 1 is notated as Q i (s, a i; i), which depends on learnable parameters i."
  ]
}